Protocols Used at Each Layer
The protocols change dynamically as data moves up the stack, shifting from low-power local networks to robust internet communication:
1. IoT Sensor Nodes → Gateway (Edge Layer)
Devices at this layer are highly constrained in terms of power, memory, and processing. They use lightweight, short-range communication protocols:
LoRaWAN / LoRa: For long-range, low-power outdoor deployments (e.g., smart agriculture).
Zigbee / Z-Wave: For low-power, short-range mesh networking (e.g., smart homes).
BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy): For personal area networks and wearable tech.
Modbus / BACnet: Common legacy wired protocols used in industrial and automation environments.
2. Gateway → Cloud (Network/Transport Layer)
The gateway aggregates this data and pushes it over long distances to the cloud using standard TCP/IP network interfaces (Ethernet, Wi-Fi, 4G/5G Cellular):
MQTT: A lightweight, publish/subscribe messaging protocol optimal for unreliable or restricted bandwidth networks.
HTTP / HTTPS (REST APIs): Used for standard data uploads, configuration updates, or heavy payloads (like image files).
CoAP (Constrained Application Protocol): A UDP-based protocol designed for machine-to-machine (M2M) translation with low overhead.
AMQP (Advanced Message Queuing Protocol): Used in enterprise environments requiring high-reliability transactional messaging.
3. Cloud → User Application (Application Layer)
Once the data is in the cloud, standard web and enterprise protocols are used to pipe information directly to mobile apps, web dashboards, or API endpoints:
HTTPS (REST APIs): To fetch historical data, trigger actions, or handle user authentication.
WebSockets: Used to stream live, bi-directional, real-time data directly onto the user's dashboard screen without constant polling.
gRPC / GraphQL: Utilized for high-performance, efficient data querying between backend cloud services and front-end user apps.
